COREDUMPER(1)               General Commands Manual              COREDUMPER(1)

NNAAMMEE
     ccoorreedduummppeerr â€“ crash detector and core dumper

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
     ccoorreedduummppeerr [--cc _C_O_R_E_N_A_M_E] [--ii] [--oo _O_U_T_P_U_T] [--pp | ccoommmmaanndd [_a_r_g _._._.]]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
     ccoorreedduummppeerr traces specified process and dumps core for crashes.  Certain
     programs handle program crashes with signal handlers, preventing core(5)
     files from being generated.  ccoorreedduummppeerr bypasses their signal handlers
     and for each crash dumps core, without changing capturing mechanism in
     traced processes.

     The options are as follows:

     --cc _C_O_R_E_N_A_M_E
             Specifies core file name.  If not set, the default value is
             selected.  The syntax is specified in core(5).

     --ii      Inherit; pass the trace flags to all future children of the
             designated processes.

     --pp _P_I_D  Enable (disable) tracing on the indicated process id (only one --pp
             flag is permitted).

     _c_o_m_m_a_n_d [_a_r_g_s _._._.]
             Execute _c_o_m_m_a_n_d with the specified trace flags.

     The --pp and _c_o_m_m_a_n_d options are mutually exclusive.

IIMMPPLLEEMMEENNTTAATTIIOONN NNOOTTEESS
     The tracer uses the ptrace(2) system call to perform the tracing process.

     Similar functionality can be achieved with a debugger like gdb(1),
     however ccoorreedduummppeerr is quicker and easier to setup for one specific task.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
     # detect crashes and generate core dumps for an X session
           $ coredumper -i startx

     # detect crashes and generate core dumps for a running browser
           $ coredumper -i -p firefox

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
     gdb(1), picotrace(1), ptrace(2)

HHIISSTTOORRYY
     Tn ccoorreedduummppeerr command was designed for NetBSD 9.

AAUUTTHHOORRSS
     Kamil Rytarowski <_k_a_m_i_l_@_N_e_t_B_S_D_._o_r_g>

